{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654286"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18610"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18610"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76409"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61906"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10265"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26335"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76409"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA person holds a heavy book steady with their arm extended at 90 degrees from their body. The biceps muscle maintains a constant position despite the downward force of gravity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of muscle contraction occurring in the biceps?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Muscle alternates between shortening and lengthening","Muscle shortens while maintaining constant tension","Muscle lengthens while generating force","Tension and length both decrease simultaneously","Tension increases without change in muscle length"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Etension increases without change in muscle length\u003C/strong\u003E. This describes an isometric contraction, where the muscle generates force to match the load (in this case gravity acting on the book) while maintaining a fixed length. The muscle fibres are actively generating cross-bridge cycles but the opposing forces are balanced, resulting in no net movement.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle shortens while maintaining constant tension\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes isotonic concentric contraction, which occurs during muscle shortening\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle lengthens while generating force\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes eccentric contraction, where the muscle lengthens under tension\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETension and length both decrease simultaneously\u003C/strong\u003E - This combination does not occur in normal muscle physiology\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle alternates between shortening and lengthening\u003C/strong\u003E - This would describe oscillating movement rather than maintaining a static position\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EIsometric contractions are particularly important for postural control and joint stabilisation, where muscles need to generate force without changing length to maintain a fixed position against gravity or other forces.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Isometric muscle contraction occurs when muscle tension increases but length remains constant.","During isometric contraction, the force generated by the muscle equals the opposing load.","Isometric contractions are important for maintaining posture and stabilising joints."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61906"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18610"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61906"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T13:31:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T13:31:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76409"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4